arch:property.oc:show_val: Changed from L1 in top 2m of trench because we hit an area of harder soil that may be mudbrick debris. The surface was riddled with animal holes. There is a color change to a darker brown that can be seen in section. Most likely this is subtopsoil, it was difficult to figure out the difference between top soil and subtopsoil so L1 and L2 are mixed. We separated L2 and L4 earlier in the season but found that they were equal so we opened L2 again stratigraphy wise that is not the best choice but luckily we did not excavate L2 under L4 and merely changed to L5 instead. THis locus was poorly excavated because it was difficult to keep track of over the course of the season and was dropped from a few day plans then closed without giving it a definite closing date. The date above should be correct.
this locus was mixed with the north edge of L3 (walls and ash) and L4 which it equals
pebbles, some potsherds, roots, animal holes
hard compacted areas mixed with softer areas further north, red brown color recedes as you head north

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
